## 12. Implementation Checklist

Use this checklist to verify your implementation covers all required behaviors:

### Persistence
- [ ] `currentTerm`, `votedFor`, and `log[]` are persisted to stable storage before any RPC response is sent.
- [ ] On server restart, these values are restored from disk.

### Leader Election
- [ ] Election timeout is randomized from a configurable range (e.g., 150–300ms).
- [ ] Election timer resets on: valid AppendEntries received, vote granted, conversion to candidate.
- [ ] Candidate increments term, votes for self, sends RequestVote to all peers.
- [ ] Candidate becomes leader only upon receiving a majority of votes for the current term.
- [ ] Vote is granted only if: `votedFor` is null or matches `candidateId`, AND candidate's log is at least as up-to-date.
- [ ] Log up-to-date comparison uses last entry's term first, then length.
- [ ] Server steps down to follower if it sees a higher term in any RPC.

### Log Replication
- [ ] Leader appends client commands to its log with the current term.
- [ ] Leader sends AppendEntries with correct `prevLogIndex` and `prevLogTerm`.
- [ ] Follower rejects AppendEntries if `prevLogIndex`/`prevLogTerm` don't match.
- [ ] Follower truncates conflicting entries (same index, different term) and appends new ones.
- [ ] Leader decrements `nextIndex` on AppendEntries failure and retries.
- [ ] Leader updates `nextIndex` and `matchIndex` on AppendEntries success.
- [ ] Leader advances `commitIndex` only when a majority has replicated an entry AND that entry is from the current term.

### Commitment and Application
- [ ] Entries are applied to the state machine in log index order.
- [ ] Entries are applied only after they are committed (`commitIndex >= entry index`).
- [ ] `lastApplied` tracks the most recently applied entry.
- [ ] Leader only counts replicas for entries from its own term to advance `commitIndex`.

### Heartbeats
- [ ] Leader sends periodic heartbeats (empty AppendEntries) to all followers.
- [ ] Heartbeat interval is much less than minimum election timeout.

### Snapshotting
- [ ] Server takes snapshots when log exceeds a size threshold.
- [ ] Snapshot includes: state machine state, `lastIncludedIndex`, `lastIncludedTerm`, current cluster configuration.
- [ ] Log entries up to and including `lastIncludedIndex` are discarded after snapshotting.
- [ ] Leader sends InstallSnapshot RPC to followers that need entries the leader has already discarded.
- [ ] Follower discards its log and resets state machine when receiving a snapshot that supersedes its log.

### Client Interaction
- [ ] Non-leader servers redirect clients to the leader.
- [ ] Client commands include unique serial numbers for deduplication.
- [ ] State machine caches the result of the last command per client and serves cached responses for duplicate serial numbers.
- [ ] Read-only requests require the leader to confirm leadership (heartbeat exchange with majority) before responding.
- [ ] Leader commits a no-op entry at the start of each term.

### RPCs
- [ ] All RPCs are idempotent (safe to retry on timeout).
- [ ] RPCs are retried indefinitely until they succeed.
- [ ] RPCs are sent in parallel for performance.
- [ ] Every RPC response includes the sender's `currentTerm`.

### Cluster Membership Changes
- [ ] Configuration changes go through joint consensus (`C_old,new` then `C_new`).
- [ ] During joint consensus, separate majorities from both old and new configurations are required.
- [ ] New servers catch up as non-voting members before entering the configuration.
- [ ] Leader steps down after committing `C_new` if it is not in the new configuration.
- [ ] Servers disregard RequestVote RPCs received within the minimum election timeout of the last heartbeat from a leader.

